That would save memory, but the original code does store the array. But since the array is not used again after filling gen, perhaps the Fortran code can avoid storing it. Let's see. Original code:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    arr[i] = in.nextInt();
    gen[arr[i]]++;
}

So the array arr is stored, but then only used to fill gen. So perhaps in Fortran, we can just read each number into a temporary variable and update gen accordingly.
